segments.text: information on yourself, like your name and where you were born and when you were born, if you don't mind?
Well, I don't usually tell that.
Well, that's just fine.
But I was born in Madisonville, Texas, over here just 45 miles from College Station.
My family moved to Amarillo, Texas, when I was quite young.
And my father practiced law in Amarillo.
I went through public schools in Amarillo.
And then went to West Texas State for two years and then to the University of Texas for two years where I received my degree in French and Latin of all the things.
But I used those later because I taught for a while in Amarillo and then I came to Bryan to teach in Bryan High School and I taught French and Latin in Bryan High School.
But that didn't last too long because I met my husband-to-be the day after I arrived in Bryan.
I've always thought that was kind of interesting.
We were married then in 1929.
And he had his master's degree, his bachelor's and his master's degrees from the University of Chicago.
But he always had the ambition to get that PhD.
because he was teaching here in the chemistry department.
He wanted the PhD.
So we went to Colorado the first summer after he was married.
And he tried to get a degree program set up at the University of Colorado, but he wasn't satisfied.
So the next six summers, we went to Chicago, and he completed the clerk for his PhD.
They told him at that time that it was the best thing for him to come in summers because of the fact that that was depression time.
And if he had a job, he ought to keep it.
They said, we'll take care of you in the summers.
But we don't want you giving up a job to come up here and finish it in the required time it would take for long sessions.
He received his degree.
And 37.
We have two sons.
One of them went three years to A&M.
The other one went four years to A&M.
Both have completed degrees and are doctors.
One is a pediatrician in Denver, Colorado.
The other is a psychiatrist and has just recently moved to Bryan.
He built our home in 1936 and lived in this house ever since.
So the reason you came to Bryan, did your family move here?
No, I had relatives in Bryan, and they persuaded me to come here and teach.
In fact, they helped secure the job for me because at that time it was hard to get a job.
job for a teacher.
And the curious thing about it, they would not let women who were married teach in the Bryan schools at that time.
So when we were married, I had to give up my job teaching.
Now, all women that want to teach can if they're equipped for it.
OK.
When you came here, what was the town of Bryan College Station
Combined like it is now, or was it College Station small?
Oh, no, it wasn't very much between the two.
College Station hadn't grown up very much.
In fact, when we built this house, there was nothing south of us.
Now it just extends for miles out south of us.
But the only road to College Station at that time was the one over by the railroad track.
and that's where you came to College Station from Bryan at that time.
Later, we were very delighted when they opened Jersey Street and opened Texas Avenue.
Texas Avenue had not extended out very far, but when we built here, we were about the fourth house on this street.
About the fourth house.
Well, did the
Was the town of College Station, did it group around the main street, or was it just centered around the university itself?
Oh, just the university.
That was it.
Northgate was the center of the business life of College Station.
And at the time we moved here, no students were allowed to have cars on the campus.
No students were allowed to have cars, we'll put it that way, because boys would come here and offer to rent
our garage so that they could keep a car and attend school and not let the authorities know they had cars in this community.
The East Gate didn't grow up until four years later after that.
And the wood stores on Jersey didn't be up there until after that.
been living here for a while.
Was there a distinction between, were there different classes of people, like rich people, lower class?
Were there distinctions between black and white at that time?
At that time, there were some colored sections around.
But the people of the university, it was the college for so long, were just about on the same level.
I mean, financially and our homes and everything of that sort.
We didn't have any rich people.
We just had college professors are never rich.
We live just about like everybody else around here.
Well, now, do you remember any severe weather events such as any droughts or floods or anything of that type?
No, I remember one time when the temperature dropped to six below zero.
And people really suffered because houses aren't built here for that kind of weather.
And many pipes froze and many pipes burst.
But we were fortunate in not having any trouble at our home.
Has the weather, like, did it used to snow here more often, or was it just about like it is now?
Just about as it is now.
We never did have snow every year.
Some years we'd have heavy snow.
Two years ago, if you were here, you'd remember that we had snow that lasted for over a week.
But this year, I haven't seen any snow.
They said there were a few flakes in the morning.
Did...
What was the town?
Was it an incorporated town?
Did it have a mayor?
What was the political... How was it run?
At first, we did not.
Then, Mr. McNew, I believe, was the moving spirit in having the town incorporated.
I don't remember very much about how it was run before that.
Well, have you noticed...
a shift in the livelihood activities of the people here?
Like, has it changed from agricultural?
I know the city's grown, but would you say there was about as many agricultural activity then as now, or was it more toward agriculture then?
This has always been a cotton-growing country around here, and the Brazos Bottom has been
the source of much of the wealth that has been in Bryan all these years.
The farms I believe now, they are more, I think they've been sold to bigger corporations.
There used to be lots of smaller farms in the bottom.
But outside of that, there hasn't been too much agriculture anymore.
Well now, when we moved here, were electricity and telephones already installed?
Yes, yes.
But when I first came to Bryan, there was no gas.
All homes were heated then by, mostly by fireplaces.
But they brought gas in, and old people were so delighted when they brought gas in, but they had electricity before I came, and sewer, and everything like that.
You mentioned, you know, the road system, how it was just the Weldon Highway that connected
You mentioned that they opened up Texas.
Was that a highway then?
Did it go all the way to Madison like it does now?
Is that when they opened it?
Not for a while.
We had to go through Wellborn and Milliken to go to Houston before the Texas Highway was built.
And I can't think what it was called before it became Texas.
That means Houston Highway, I guess.
Yeah.
Do you remember about what time they opened the road back just around what years?
No.
I know that when we first moved here, our streets weren't paved.
There was a little gravel put on them, but numerous people were stuck in our driveway.
And in the curb, near the curb, we didn't get
Really didn't get the curbs and gutters until, oh, the 50s, I guess.
College Station started a paving.
Would you say that the College Station brine area has grown faster in the last 10 years than so before?
Yes.
I think the reason for that is that the university has grown so fast.
Right now, it seems to me that it's growing faster than it ever has.
The customs, you know, I'm sure they've changed quite a bit from back when you first came here.
Let's say the food.
Did most people buy their food, or was there a lot of growing food and selling it from the land itself?
There used to be a farmer's market in Brown where we made it a point to go every Saturday.
They had it, I believe, on Wednesday and Saturday.
And we were able to procure fresh vegetables and fruits at times.
But we were all delighted when the first market came in here.
I think A&P was probably the first that came in.
We noticed the prices went down in the grocery stores after this supermarket business began to come into our community.
At that time, we could drive to Houston and buy groceries and save enough to pay for our trip to Houston.
There was quite a chain of business there.
Just a few old-timers had stores in Brown, and they kept the store prices high.
Well, then what about the grants?
I'm sure that's changed.
Well, it's changed just as it has all over the country, because after all, America's pretty much the same, and particularly now since TV.
And social life has changed since we've had TV.
And air conditioning, those two things have changed.
We used to visit people more than we do now, and people used to visit us more.
And we had more of our homemade social life, I'll call it, at that time, because people didn't sit in front of the TV, and they weren't comfortable with the air condition that's the way they are now.
Well, did y'all...
The different people give parties back then?
Yes.
I remember soon after we were married that I would have a party, maybe have 40 or 50 people for dinner.
I haven't done that in a long time.
We could get help that would make it easier for us at that time.
Well, what about...
entertainment as far as outside people?
Did College Station Bryan area get many what you call big name entertainers to come and visit?
There has never been a time here where there wasn't something going on.
It used to be called Town Hall and met in Gine Hall.
That's where we saw plays.
We heard the famous
opera singers, and good programs were brought in at that time, just as they are now.
What was the police force like?
Did they have a police force?
Did they need one about the law and order?
Was it pretty well acquired?
This has never been a very...
wild community so far as crime is concerned.
I've heard of a few burglaries in this neighborhood, but that's the only crime I've ever heard of.
Okay, now what about the fire department?
Did they have a fire department here?
We had to use the college fire department.
It hasn't been very many years that College Station itself had a real fire department.
Now I think it's switched, and the university uses the College Station fire department now.
OK. You were in the school system.
You might mention a little bit how it was run, about not being able to be married and teach.
How was the weather?
Would you consider the school system was good for this area?
Well, see, I taught in Bryan, and there was a separate system at College Station at the time.
I thought the Bryan system was a pretty good system.
We had about all the courses that most high schools offer now.
And I thought it was a really good system.
Because there was one high school?
Oh, yes.
Weren't there two schools in Brown at that time?
One was on the west side and one was on the east side.
Were the schools, did they have a black school and a white school?
Oh, yes.
Yes, the school was part of the blacks in Brown.
Then later, I don't know about College Station schools at that time, but I know later there were.
and Scooby-Doo as far as that at College Station.
You might mention a little bit about the Depression.
Do you remember, of course, the effects, I'm sure, reached everywhere in the US, but do you remember the conditions, some of the living conditions, like as far as transportation, means of income?
Did people get along, or were they hard-pressed?
Well, it was hard.
I remember that during the Depression, my husband was paid for, since we were going to Chicago every summer, we were paid for his nine months.
And we had to live on that money during the rest of the year.
So there was no extravagance at that time.
You can count on that.
Then I believe that was the time when
We had to discount the warrants.
We were paid in warrants, and then they had to be discounted.
We'd go up to the bank, and they'd charge us so much to cash them, you know.
That was, it wasn't easy, because the salaries were low then, too.
Well, were the prices, did they go up, or were they about the same as far as food?
Well, they were much lower than they are today.
But it made up, it was still harder because of the time.
Oh, yes.
Because of the time, it was harder.
Do you remember any of the programs that President Roosevelt came out with affecting any of this area around here, such as the WPA and the RA?
I can't remember that very much was done here.
I have seen buildings in other cities.
that were built at that time.
I remember that my brother-in-law was a doctor and he went to a CC camp and worked because it was hard at that time for a doctor to make a living.
What effect did

Would you say that World War II, did it have on the community here, A&M being a military school then, did it take anything away from the community, or did the community have to do without as far as certain commodities?
There was an Air Force base out from Bryan, and that brought in a lot of money to the community that wouldn't have been here.
It was a training for fighter bombers, I believe.
And that brought in money that helped the community here.
We had the same sort of situation that was everywhere at that time because we had our little stamps that we used to buy food.
We had the
One, all in places when we'd hear there was sugar, several of us would go together and go to town to try to get some of that sugar that had come in.
We had just about the same conditions here that were all over.
Okay.
What about the churches?
Were there many different churches here?
Just the same that there are now.
There may be a few.
different ones now, but the main churches were, I don't believe the Catholics built out here for a while, but the Church of Christ was needed at that time because they made it the library.
I don't mean the library, I mean the YMCA.
The Baptist Church was moving, the Methodist.
I can't remember that, the Episcopal.
The Presbyterian was moving at that time.
What about, did much building go on during the Depression or during World War II as far as the university or the houses and communities?
Did it grow much during that period of time?
Not very much during that time.
Would you say it lost or just stayed about the same?
I would say it didn't stay about the same because where there's a school, like A&M, of course the enrollment got down.
I don't know.
I can't remember if there was much change, though, on account of the World War II.
I was trying to think.
I read a letter that my husband had written me when I went on a visit, and he was telling me that they thought they were going to have 5,000 students, and they were very delighted of it.
They thought that was going to be this real deal for them.
What about the railroads?
Would you say that the towns that first grew up around the railroads and then moved on to other places?
Oh, the railroads was the center of the community.
We had three trains to Dallas every day.
There was one in the morning, one in the afternoon, and then one in the night.
And to Houston, of course, the same number.
We had two trains through here at that time.
That was really the center of transportation at that time.
Well, that's just about all the questions that I had, particularly.
I can tell you something that was very interesting.
The water in College Station was a sulfur calc water.
And we couldn't leave any of it overnight in an aluminum pan.
We did.
We got up in the morning and saw the bubbles all over the pan.
We had to watch that very carefully.
And our silver garnished very easily from that water.
We were happy when we got some new water.
Did y'all have individual wells then?
It was always piped in.
We used city water.
Would you say that the A&M changed, the college changed since the Corps wasn't mandatory?
Would you say it was more military type then?
Did that change the town?
Have any effect on the town that you can remember?
I don't know that it did.
Maybe the social life among the Corps was a little more than I hear of now.
I know that
I have, along with many other people in this community, have rented rooms on weekends to girls who came for festivities on the campus.
There were no hotels except for the old Aggieland Inn on the campus.
And Brown didn't have very many hotels.
So they used to phone and say, can you take three girls or two girls?
Some family would come in and visit.
Now it's very different with so many motels and hotels around.
Would you say that most of the families that lived in College Station were professors to the university?
Would you say that's what made up most of the town?
Yes.
It's been that way.
Until recently, it seems to me that there are lots of people around now who are not connected with the university.
And this was a college, and the school wasn't so large.
Most of the people out here were connected with the university in some way.
Professors are workers.
Were there...

such days as was it hard at times to to get things to the city itself to buy such as gasoline or meats I guess meats and agriculture it wouldn't be that big a thing since that took place here but just during the war we had trouble getting things we used the system of
neighbors going in together to do our transportation during the war.
But after the war, we have had no coverage of anything.
Can you think of any influential families, names that stand out of individual families of the area that have owned quite a bit or more or less, you know,
influence the community to a big extent or would you say it's mostly been just a community working together?
It seems to me it's more just a community working together.
Mr. Burgess and a few people like that have developed places.
Now, Mr. Burgess developed this section of the community and he also developed the
what was called North Oakwood.
This was South Oakwood, and that was North Oakwood.
Then there was a group that developed the section to the west of this.
But it has, there hasn't been any, just real leader in developing things and growing, building things.
Just various individuals.
Oh.
Were the families that lived here then that were mostly faculty of the A&M school, since they had a lot in common, was it a closer knit community than it is now, do you think?
Yes.
I attribute part of that, though, to the fact that people have TVs and air conditioning.
That makes a difference.
I know that we used to have book clubs here.
We'd have maybe people on two or three streets would each buy a book, and then we'd pass those on.
So maybe we read a little more at that time.
So you were saying that the TV made a big difference in social life here, but just everywhere too.
Oh yes, everywhere.
It's not just community.
Did y'all used to listen to the radio as the main media?
Yes, we did.
We had a radio from... We bought it right after we married.
It was the center of a lot of our entertainment, you might say.
You had mentioned that your relatives were the ones that persuaded you to come here to this area at first.
Why were they in this area, do you know?
Well, I mentioned that that was Mrs. Coker who called me on the phone.
Her father had moved here to set up that Allen Academy, the school.
And then I had a cousin in Bryant whose husband was a doctor.
I had another cousin whose husband was a druggist.
I had an uncle who was a banker.
And these people just entertained me when I came to visit before that, and then they suggested that I come down here and teach school.
Do you know where your family is from as far as before they came to Texas?
My mother's people came from Tennessee, and my father's people came from Mississippi.
My husband's people were English, Scotch-Irish is what he said.
My people were, my mother's people were, some of them from Italy and some from
Well, I don't know.
What other country?
And my father's people were Swedish.
Would you say that any particular nationality grouped together anywhere around this area?
Like, you know, in central Texas it's Polish and Czech peoples, and then down towards San Antonio it's Germans.
Would you say this area was more or less
mixed as far as nationalities?
Yes, there is a big Italian group here, and also there is a big Czech group.
I know a man whose mother, to this day, doesn't speak English.
She still speaks Czech.
